# Go Project — Claude Code Instructions

_Origin: https://github.com/maxart/Go-with-AI — check upstream for newer versions of this file._

## Identity

You are working on a production Go backend service — typically an HTTP/gRPC API or worker that runs on AWS (Lambda, ECS Fargate, EKS, or EC2), or on an NVIDIA-GPU host (EC2 G/P-family, EKS with the GPU Operator, NVIDIA DGX Cloud, NVIDIA Cloud Functions). Follow modern best practices (2025-2026, Go 1.24+). Write clean, idiomatic, type-safe, secure code that scales horizontally. Prioritize correctness, clarity, observability, and operational simplicity. Don't over-engineer. Go rewards small, sharp, boring code.

---

## Output and Efficiency

- Return code first. Explanation after, only if non-obvious. No sycophantic openers, closing fluff, or restating the question.
- No unsolicited suggestions or boilerplate beyond the requested scope. Read before writing — one focused pass, avoid write-delete-rewrite cycles.
- If unsure, say so. Never guess Go stdlib APIs, AWS SDK v2 client method shapes, or `go.mod` directives. Code output is ASCII only.
- Code review: state the bug, show the fix, stop. Debugging: read first, state what/where/fix.
- User instructions always override this file.

---

## Code Quality Rules

- Write the simplest code that solves the problem. **A little copying is better than a little dependency** (Go proverb) — don't pull in a library for one helper. No speculative abstractions.
- **Errors are values.** Return `error` from anything that can fail. Never `panic` for expected failures (only truly unrecoverable startup bugs). `log.Fatal` only in `main`.
- **Accept interfaces, return concrete types.** Define the interface in the **consumer** package, not the producer. Tiny interfaces (1-3 methods) are best. `io.Reader`, `io.Writer`, `error` are the model.
- One package per directory. Package name = directory name (lowercase, single word, no underscores). No circular imports — compiler enforces.
- Don't comment what the code says. Only comment non-obvious "why". Doc-comments on every **exported** identifier, starting with the identifier name (required by `revive`). Remove dead code; don't keep it "for reference".
- `gofmt` is mandatory and non-negotiable. Run `goimports` on save. CI fails on formatting drift.

### Naming

- Packages: short, lowercase, no plural (`user` not `users`); no `util`/`common`/`helpers` (meaningless dumping grounds). Avoid stuttering: `http.Handler` not `http.HTTPHandler`.
- Exported `PascalCase`; unexported `camelCase`. Acronyms uniform case (`URL`, `HTTPClient`, `userID` — not `userId`). Receivers: 1-2 letters, consistent across all methods on the type. Never `self`/`this`.
- Errors: variables `ErrNotFound`; types `NotFoundError`. Interfaces: single-method ends in `-er` (`Reader`, `UserStore`). Test files `_test.go`; `BenchmarkXxx`, `ExampleXxx`. Constants: `PascalCase`/`camelCase` — never `UPPER_SNAKE` (that's C).

---

## Go Language Rules

### Modules, Generics, Iterators

- One `go.mod` per module at repo root; `go 1.24`+ directive matches CI. `go mod tidy` before every commit; commit `go.sum`. Never edit `require` by hand — `go get pkg@version`. One major bump per PR. Imports grouped: stdlib / third-party / local, blank-line separated (`goimports`).
- Concrete types in signatures. Generics only when you'd otherwise duplicate code or use `any`. Never generic-ify for "future flexibility". Use `any`, not `interface{}`. Range-over-function iterators (1.23+) for streaming only; plain slices for collections. Defined types (`type UserID string`) over aliases for new domain types.

### Errors

- Wrap with `%w`: `fmt.Errorf("get user %s: %w", id, err)`. Never `%v` for inner errors (loses chain). Sentinel errors (`var ErrNotFound = errors.New(...)`) checked with `errors.Is`; custom error types checked with `errors.As`. Don't compare `err.Error()` strings.
- Don't `if err != nil { return err }` blindly — add context unless the immediate caller will. `errors.Join` (1.20+) for aggregation. Never swallow — `_ = x.Close()` is a smell.
- `panic`/`recover` only at process boundaries (HTTP middleware turning panics into 500s, `main` recovery). Never for control flow. `log.Fatal` only in `main`.

### Pointers, Slices, Maps, Defer

- Pointers when value is large, you need to mutate, type has a mutex, or nil is meaningful. Otherwise pass by value — escape analysis is good, value semantics are safer.
- Slices: nil is valid for read; `make([]T, 0, cap)` when capacity known. Slicing aliases the backing array — `slices.Clone` to detach.
- Maps: no concurrent writes without `sync.Mutex` (or `sync.Map` when keys stable + reads dominate). Iteration order randomized.
- `defer` for cleanup at the top of the function after acquiring the resource. Defers in loops accumulate — close inline or factor out.

---

## Project Structure

```
service/
  cmd/
    api/main.go           # HTTP server entry point
    worker/main.go        # background processor
    migrate/main.go       # schema migrations
  internal/               # private; not importable outside this module
    config/               # env loading, validation
    http/                 # router, middleware, handlers
    user/                 # domain: user.go, store.go, service.go,
                          #   store_postgres.go, service_test.go
    platform/
      database/, awsx/, logger/, otelx/   # *pgxpool.Pool, SDK v2, slog, OTel
  pkg/                    # public; rare — most services have none
  api/                    # OpenAPI specs, protobuf .proto files
  migrations/             # SQL migrations (golang-migrate format)
  Dockerfile, Makefile, go.mod, go.sum, .golangci.yml, .env.example
```

- `cmd/<binary>/main.go` = **wiring only**: load config, build deps, start server, handle shutdown. No business logic. One subdirectory per binary.
- Default to `internal/` (Go enforces privacy). Use `pkg/` only for code genuinely meant for external import.
- Organize `internal/` by **domain** (`user/`, `order/`, `billing/`), not technical layer (`handlers/`, `services/`, `repos/`). Each domain package owns its types, interfaces, store impl, service. Cross-domain code in a coordinating package or `cmd/`.
- Avoid `util`/`common`/`helpers`/`models` packages — they become dumping grounds. Name packages by what they provide.

---

## HTTP Server (net/http, Go 1.22+)

- **Default to stdlib `net/http`.** The 1.22 enhanced `ServeMux` supports method matching (`"GET /users/{id}"`), path wildcards (`r.PathValue("id")`), exact-path `{$}`. Enough for most services — no `gin`/`echo`/`chi`/`fiber` needed. Reach for `chi` only if you need rich middleware; `echo`/`gin` only on team familiarity. Method mismatch auto-returns 405 with `Allow`.
- Handlers are `http.HandlerFunc` or types implementing `http.Handler`. Inject deps via a struct (`type API struct { users *user.Service; logger *slog.Logger }`), method handlers off it.
- Always set `http.Server.ReadHeaderTimeout`/`ReadTimeout`/`WriteTimeout`/`IdleTimeout` and `MaxHeaderBytes`. **Default zero values are Slowloris bait.** Graceful shutdown: catch `SIGINT`/`SIGTERM`, `server.Shutdown(ctx)` with a 30s deadline, then close DB pools and flush observability.
- Middleware = `func(http.Handler) http.Handler`. Chain via composition or a tiny helper (no framework needed for chaining). Standard order: panic recovery → request ID → logger → tracing → auth → CORS → rate-limit → handler.

```go
// internal/http/handlers/users.go
type API struct{ users *user.Service; logger *slog.Logger }

func (a *API) handleGetUser(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    id, err := uuid.Parse(r.PathValue("id"))
    if err != nil { writeError(w, http.StatusBadRequest, "invalid user id"); return }
    u, err := a.users.GetByID(r.Context(), id)
    if errors.Is(err, user.ErrNotFound) { writeError(w, http.StatusNotFound, "not found"); return }
    if err != nil {
        a.logger.ErrorContext(r.Context(), "get user", "err", err, "user_id", id)
        writeError(w, http.StatusInternalServerError, "internal error"); return
    }
    writeJSON(w, http.StatusOK, userDTO{ID: u.ID, Email: u.Email}) // DTO, not domain type
}
```

- Decode: `json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&v)` then `defer r.Body.Close()`. Set `dec.DisallowUnknownFields()` for strict APIs. Cap body with `http.MaxBytesReader` (~1 MiB) before decoding.
- **Never** return raw domain or DB structs as JSON — define a DTO per endpoint. Avoids leaking internal fields, accidental exposure on refactor, and coupling wire format to storage.
- Error responses: stable shape `{"error":{"code":"...","message":"..."}}`. Don't echo internal errors; map to safe public messages. Log the full error server-side with request ID. Status codes: 200 OK, 201 Created (+ `Location`), 204, 400 client, 401, 403, 404, 409, 422 validation, 429, 5xx. Never 200 with `"success":false`.

---

## Context, Concurrency, Cancellation

- **First parameter of every blocking / I/O function is `ctx context.Context`.** Pass it through; never store in a struct (lint: `containedctx`). In handlers use `r.Context()` — never `context.Background()`.
- `context.WithTimeout` / `WithDeadline` at the boundary where you decide the budget (handler entry, outbound call, DB query). Always `defer cancel()`. Don't add per-call timeouts inside library code — let callers decide.
- Check `ctx.Err()` after `select`. `context.Cause(ctx)` (1.20+) returns the underlying reason — log that. `context.WithValue` only for request-scoped data crossing API boundaries (request ID, principal, trace span); never for optional args; use unexported key types (`type ctxKey int`).
- **Goroutines** must have an obvious termination path. Naked `go fn()` in a long-running service is a leak. Use `golang.org/x/sync/errgroup` for parallel work that should fail-fast: first non-nil error cancels the group context and is returned by `Wait()`. `sync.WaitGroup` only when you don't need error aggregation. Prefer channels for handoff, mutexes for state. `sync.RWMutex` only when reads vastly dominate (measure first).
- Channel rules: the **sender** closes (closing a closed channel panics). Buffered for hand-off; unbuffered for sync. `nil` channel in `select` is never selected.
- `go test -race ./...` in CI. Any `WARNING: DATA RACE` is a release blocker.

---

## Database Access (PostgreSQL with pgx + sqlc)

- **Default**: `jackc/pgx/v5` driver + `sqlc` for type-safe query generation. `lib/pq` is in maintenance mode — don't pick for new code. Use `database/sql` only for driver portability (rare).
- One `*pgxpool.Pool` per process at startup. Tune `MaxConns` (= app concurrency cap, often 10-25/pod), `MinConns`, `MaxConnLifetime` (~30m), `MaxConnIdleTime`. Pass the pool (or a generated `Querier`) into stores.
- `sqlc` generates a typed `Queries` struct from hand-written SQL in `db/queries/*.sql`. **Don't** hand-write methods that duplicate what sqlc generates. Always pass `ctx` — pgx honors cancellation.
- **Transactions**: `tx, err := pool.BeginTx(ctx, ...)`; `defer tx.Rollback(ctx)` (no-op if committed); `tx.Commit(ctx)` at the end. Keep them **short** — long transactions hold locks.
- **Never** build SQL with `fmt.Sprintf` from user input. Parameter placeholders (`$1`, `$2`). For dynamic `IN (...)` use `pgx.NamedArgs` or `=ANY($1)` with arrays. sqlc makes injection nearly impossible.
- Store interface lives in the **domain package** (`type Store interface { Create(ctx, ...) (User, error); ... }`); impl `store_postgres.go` wraps sqlc `Queries`. Services depend on the interface, not the impl — enables in-memory fakes for tests.
- Migrations: `golang-migrate` (or `goose`/`atlas`). Versioned SQL in `migrations/`. Run via `cmd/migrate/main.go` or a separate task. **Append-only in production.** Connect with retry+backoff at startup; fail-fast on bad DSN. `pool.Ping(ctx)` in readiness probe.

```go
// internal/user/store_postgres.go
type PgStore struct{ q *db.Queries } // *db.Queries from sqlc

func (s *PgStore) GetByID(ctx context.Context, id uuid.UUID) (User, error) {
    row, err := s.q.GetUserByID(ctx, id)
    if errors.Is(err, pgx.ErrNoRows) { return User{}, ErrNotFound }
    if err != nil { return User{}, fmt.Errorf("get user %s: %w", id, err) }
    return User{ID: row.ID, Email: row.Email, CreatedAt: row.CreatedAt.Time}, nil
}
```

---

## AWS SDK for Go v2

- **Always v2** (`github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/...`). v1 reached end-of-support **July 31, 2025** — migrate any v1 holdouts; don't start anything new on it.
- Load config once at startup: `cfg, err := config.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx, config.WithRegion(region))`. Reuse one `aws.Config` to construct service clients. Service clients are safe for concurrent use — keep as singletons.
- **Credentials**: never access keys in env vars or files in containers. Use IAM roles — task role (ECS/Fargate), execution role (Lambda), IRSA (EKS), instance profile (EC2). The default credential chain finds them.
- **Region** from `AWS_REGION` env (set automatically on Lambda/ECS); fail-fast if unset elsewhere. Pass `ctx` to every API call. Configure retries (`config.WithRetryMaxAttempts(5)`, adaptive mode for high-throughput).
- Use **paginators** (`s3.NewListObjectsV2Paginator(client, input)`) — never hand-roll `NextToken` loops.
- Don't override `BaseEndpoint` outside tests / LocalStack. For LocalStack/Minio: per-client `o.BaseEndpoint = aws.String(endpoint)` and `o.UsePathStyle = true` for S3.
- Don't bake account-specific ARNs into code — pass via env. Don't log raw responses (PII / credentials in headers).

---

## AWS Lambda (Go)

- **Runtime**: `provided.al2023` (the `go1.x` runtime was deprecated end of 2023 — builds rejected). Binary must be named `bootstrap`, zipped at the root of the package.
- **Architecture**: `arm64` (Graviton2) — **20% cheaper, ~19% faster**. Cross-compile: `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -tags lambda.norpc -ldflags "-s -w" -trimpath -o bootstrap .` then `zip function.zip bootstrap`. Fall back to `x86_64` only if a CGO dep blocks.
- Handler: `lambda.Start(handler)` from `github.com/aws/aws-lambda-go/lambda` in `main()`. Signature `func(ctx context.Context, event EventType) (ResponseType, error)`. Event types in `github.com/aws/aws-lambda-go/events` (`APIGatewayProxyRequest`, `SQSEvent`, `DynamoDBEvent`, `S3Event`).
- **Initialize once at package level** — AWS clients, pgx pool (via RDS Proxy), config, loggers — outside `main`. The container is reused; per-invocation init burns billed time. Cold start under 60 ms is achievable on arm64 with AL2023.
- **Cold starts**: for synchronous user-facing APIs use **Provisioned Concurrency** or **SnapStart** (where available). Async paths (SQS, EventBridge) usually don't care.
- Don't run a long-lived HTTP server in Lambda — use API Gateway / ALB / Function URL. `aws-lambda-go-api-proxy` adapts `net/http` to `APIGatewayProxyRequest` (acceptable for migration; native handlers are faster).
- Logs: structured JSON to stdout via `slog.JSONHandler` — CloudWatch Logs picks them up; queryable via Logs Insights. Never `log.Println` plaintext. Don't `os.Exit` inside a handler.

---

## AWS ECS / Fargate

- One process per container. **Multi-stage Dockerfile**: stage 1 compiles; stage 2 `FROM scratch` (or `gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot`) with the binary + `ca-certificates`. Image < 20 MB. Build with `CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64` and run on Graviton (`runtimePlatform: { cpuArchitecture: ARM64 }`). **Fargate has no GPUs** — for GPU workloads use ECS-on-EC2 or EKS with the GPU Operator (see GPU section).
- Listen on `PORT` env (default 8080), bind `0.0.0.0`. **Graceful shutdown**: ECS sends `SIGTERM` then waits `stopTimeout` (default 30s; set 30-60s) before `SIGKILL`. Trap, stop accepting, drain in-flight, close DB pools, return.
- Health checks: `/healthz` 200 with no DB hit (liveness — only fails if hung). `/readyz` checks DB ping + critical deps (fails when overloaded). Map ALB target group to `/readyz`.
- **IAM Task Role** (app's AWS calls) vs **Execution Role** (ECS pulling image, writing logs, fetching secrets) — distinct, least privilege. Don't reuse.
- Config via env vars sourced from Secrets Manager / Parameter Store via the task definition (`secrets: [{ name, valueFrom: arn:... }]`). Don't bake secrets in the image. Don't fetch per request — read once at startup.
- Logs: JSON to stdout; `awslogs` driver ships to CloudWatch. For high-volume use FireLens + Fluent Bit → S3/OpenSearch/Kinesis.
- **Fargate Spot** for interruption-tolerant workloads (batch, async workers); on-demand for user-facing. Always tolerate sudden termination. Autoscale on the right signal: CPU/mem for compute-bound; SQS depth for workers; ALB request count or target response time for HTTP. Min capacity ≥ 2 across AZs.

---

## CPU Architecture (arm64 vs amd64)

- **Default `arm64`** (Graviton2/3 on AWS) for pure-Go services — ~20% cheaper, ~19% faster. Cross-compile from any host with `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 CGO_ENABLED=0`. No emulation.
- **Choose `amd64`** when **any** of: a CGO dep lacks arm64 wheels; the workload uses CUDA / NVIDIA GPUs (drivers + ecosystem are amd64-first); a hot path needs AVX-512 / AMX; customer / on-prem constraint is x86-only.
- **Multi-arch images** (`docker buildx --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64`) only when consumers genuinely need both. Otherwise single-arch is simpler and faster to build. CGO multi-arch under buildx uses QEMU (slow); prefer native runners per arch in CI.
- Pin the arch in the task / Dockerfile / build script — implicit choices break when the host changes (Apple Silicon dev → x86 CI → Graviton prod is a common bug surface).

---

## GPU and NVIDIA Workloads

Go is the **service layer**, not the inference engine. Python (or C++) does the GPU math; Go handles routing, validation, auth, batching, observability, and quota in front of it. Don't call CUDA from Go.

- **Talk to inference servers over gRPC.** NVIDIA Triton, TGI, vLLM, NIM, and most serving stacks expose gRPC — generate a Go client from the `.proto` (`protoc --go_out --go-grpc_out`). For HTTP-only servers (Ollama, OpenAI-compatible), wrap `*http.Client` with `otelhttp.NewTransport`. **NIM** (NVIDIA Inference Microservices) is packaged-model containers with an OpenAI-compatible REST API — treat as any HTTP API, generous timeouts, stream where supported.
- **Hosting**: **NVCF** (NVIDIA Cloud Functions) for serverless GPU inference (pay per invocation, good for bursty); **DGX Cloud** for managed multi-tenant GPU clusters via hyperscaler partners; **EC2 G5/G6/P4/P5 + ECS-on-EC2 or EKS** for self-managed; **CoreWeave / Lambda Labs / RunPod** often cheapest raw GPU. **Fargate has no GPUs.** **EKS + NVIDIA GPU Operator** (itself in Go) is the standard Kubernetes pattern: pods request `nvidia.com/gpu: 1`, operator handles drivers / toolkit / MIG / monitoring.
- **Container images**: Go services that only **call** GPU servers stay on **distroless** — no GPU base image needed. Only the inference container needs `nvcr.io/nvidia/cuda:*-base-ubuntu*` and the `--gpus` / `nvidia.com/gpu` resource.
- **Architecture**: GPU hosts are predominantly **amd64** in AWS / Azure / GCP. CUDA-on-arm64 is mature on Jetson and Grace Hopper but lags broadly. Default `GOARCH=amd64` for binaries that run on GPU hosts or link CUDA libs.
- **CUDA via CGO is almost always wrong** — build complexity, race detector / pprof / delve degrade, Python ships CUDA features quarters faster, you lose the single static binary. Talk to a separate Python/C++ inference process over gRPC instead.
- **Observability**: scrape **DCGM** via `dcgm-exporter` (Prometheus format) — utilization, framebuffer, SM activity, power, temperature. Sidecar (ECS) or DaemonSet (EKS). Correlate with Go-side OTel traces by tagging spans with model name + version. Track cost-per-inference (request count × hourly GPU cost / GPU count).
- **Don't** auto-scale GPU instances aggressively — they cost 10-100x CPU per hour. Set min ≥ 1, max conservative, scale on queue depth or p95 latency, long cooldowns. Prefer **batching at the Go layer** (5-50 ms accumulation → single batched gRPC call) before adding GPU capacity.

---

## Configuration and Secrets

- Read all config from **environment variables** at startup (`os.Getenv` or a typed loader like `kelseyhightower/envconfig` / `caarlos0/env` / `sethvargo/go-envconfig`). Validate up front — fail-fast on missing/invalid.
- Define a `Config` struct in `internal/config`. One source of truth; pass it (or relevant slices) into constructors. Never read `os.Getenv` outside `internal/config`.
- **Secrets**: AWS Secrets Manager (rotate-able, versioned) or SSM Parameter Store SecureString (cheaper, no rotation). Reference from the ECS task definition / Lambda env mapping — the platform injects them as env vars. Don't fetch from Go code unless rotation requires it.
- Never log config values that may contain secrets. `log.Printf("config: %+v", cfg)` in startup is a CVE waiting to happen — implement `String()` / `LogValue()` to redact.
- Commit `.env.example` with placeholder values and required keys. Never commit `.env`. `.env` files are for local dev only; production uses the platform's mechanism.

---

## Logging (slog)

- Use `log/slog` (stdlib, 1.21+). **JSON handler in production**; text handler locally. Set the package logger in `main`; pass it down (`type Service struct { logger *slog.Logger }`). Don't use global `slog.Default()` in libraries.
- Always `*Context` variants from a handler/request: `logger.InfoContext(ctx, "user fetched", "user_id", id, "duration_ms", ms)` — lets a custom handler attach request/trace IDs, and the OTel bridge correlates logs to traces.
- **Key-value attribute pairs**, not formatted strings: `slog.Info("user fetched", "user_id", id)`, not `slog.Info(fmt.Sprintf(...))`. JSON handler indexes attrs; formatted strings can't be queried.
- Levels: `Debug` dev-only, `Info` normal ops, `Warn` recoverable anomalies, `Error` genuine failures. **Don't `Error` everything** — pages get ignored.
- **Redact secrets** via `LogValuer` or `ReplaceAttr`. Tokens, passwords, PII, card numbers — never raw. Bridge to OpenTelemetry with `otelslog` so logs carry trace IDs.

---

## Observability (OpenTelemetry, ADOT)

- Use **OpenTelemetry** for traces, metrics, and (increasingly) logs. AWS X-Ray now ingests OTLP — use **AWS Distro for OpenTelemetry (ADOT)** as the collector. Don't use the X-Ray SDK for new code; X-Ray is transitioning to OTel.
- Init `TracerProvider` + `MeterProvider` at startup; `defer shutdown()` to flush. OTLP exporter → ADOT collector sidecar (`localhost:4317` gRPC or `:4318` HTTP).
- Auto-instrument: `otelhttp.NewHandler(mux, "api")` server + `otelhttp.NewTransport` client; `otelpgx` for pgx; `otelaws` for AWS SDK v2. Adds spans, propagates trace context, emits standard semantic-convention attributes.
- Manual spans for business operations: `ctx, span := tracer.Start(ctx, "user.create"); defer span.End()`. Attach attributes; record errors (`span.RecordError(err); span.SetStatus(codes.Error, ...)`).
- Baseline metrics: HTTP request duration histogram (route, method, status), inflight requests gauge, DB query duration histogram, downstream RPC latency, business counters. Don't paper over missing logs with metrics or vice versa.
- **ECS**: ADOT collector as sidecar in the task definition. **Lambda**: ADOT as a layer. Forwards to X-Ray, CloudWatch Metrics, Prometheus, or any OTLP backend (Datadog, Honeycomb, New Relic, Grafana).
- Tag traces / metrics with deployment metadata (service, version, env, region, AZ) via OTel `Resource`. Sample 1-10% in prod for high-traffic; always-on for low-traffic.

---

## Validation and Input Handling

- Validate at the **edge** (HTTP / Lambda / SQS consumer). Reject early, return 400 with a clear shape — never let bad input reach the service layer.
- Request structs adjacent to the handler; validate with `go-playground/validator` (struct tags) or hand-rolled functions. Complex domain validation: expose a `Validate() error` method.
- Constrain sizes: body via `http.MaxBytesReader`; string length checked explicitly. Untrusted strings into URLs / SQL / shell / templates always escaped (`html/template`, `net/url.QueryEscape`, parameterized SQL, never `os/exec` with shell strings).
- Treat **all** external input as untrusted: HTTP bodies, query / path params, headers, cookies, env vars in pipelines, S3 object contents, SQS message bodies.

---

## Error Handling Patterns

- Wrap errors with **context** at each layer: `fmt.Errorf("user.GetByID id=%s: %w", id, err)`. Top of the call stack produces a debuggable chain.
- Map errors → HTTP status in the **handler** layer via `errors.Is` / `errors.As`. Service and repository layers don't know about HTTP — they return domain or wrapped errors.
- Sentinel errors at package boundaries (`var ErrNotFound = errors.New(...)`) — callers `errors.Is`. Custom error types when callers need fields — callers `errors.As`.
- Don't expose raw errors to clients. The handler logs the full chain and returns a sanitized message keyed by an error code. Public errors must not leak DB internals, paths, or stack traces.
- Production HTTP middleware **must** recover panics → 500s (log with `runtime/debug.Stack()`); without this, one bad goroutine kills the process.

---

## Security (Non-Negotiable)

- **SQL injection**: parameter placeholders only — never `fmt.Sprintf` user input into SQL. `sqlc` makes this nearly impossible. `gosec` rules `G201`/`G202` flag it.
- **Command injection**: never `exec.Command("sh", "-c", userInput)`. Use separate args (`exec.Command(cmd, arg1, arg2)`); validate `cmd` against an allow-list. `gosec G204`.
- **Path traversal**: `filepath.Clean` then check `strings.HasPrefix(cleaned, allowed)`. Never `os.Open(userInput)`.
- **SSRF**: validate user-supplied URLs — host in allow-list, scheme `https`. Custom `http.Client` with a `DialContext` blocking RFC 1918 / link-local for outbound calls accepting user URLs.
- **TLS**: `crypto/tls` with `MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12` (TLS 1.3 where you control both ends). Never `InsecureSkipVerify: true` outside tests.
- **Crypto**: `crypto/rand` for tokens/IDs/nonces — **never** `math/rand` (predictable). Passwords: `argon2id` (preferred), `bcrypt` (cost ≥ 12), or `scrypt`. Never SHA/MD5 for passwords.
- **Sessions**: opaque session IDs in **httpOnly Secure SameSite=Strict cookies** backed by Redis/DDB. If JWT: asymmetric (RS256/Ed25519) with rotation; verify `aud`/`iss`/`exp`/`nbf`; force expected `alg` (never trust header `alg`).
- **Secrets in source/logs**: `gitleaks` or `trufflehog` pre-commit; `gosec G101` flags hard-coded credentials. Never log `Authorization` headers or auth-endpoint bodies.
- **Dependencies**: `govulncheck ./...` in CI (analyzes call graph — only flags vulns you actually call). `gosec ./...` for SAST. Critical/high are release blockers. Dependabot/Renovate; one major bump per PR.
- **Races**: `go test -race ./...` in CI. Any data race is a security concern (TOCTOU, partially-constructed objects, panics).

---

## Testing

- **Stdlib `testing` is enough.** `stretchr/testify` (`require`, `assert`) is fine but optional — many teams prefer plain `if got != want { t.Fatalf(...) }`. Avoid BDD frameworks (`ginkgo`).
- **Table-driven tests** are the idiomatic pattern: slice of `{name, in, want, wantErr}` structs; `for _, tc := range cases { t.Run(tc.name, ...) }`. Use `t.Run` always (selective filtering, parallel control, clearer output). `t.Parallel()` everywhere safe — surfaces hidden ordering deps, cuts CI time. Capture loop var (`tc := tc`) for pre-1.22 code; 1.22+ scoping fixes it.
- Test **behavior**, not implementation. Test exported functions through their public surface. `pkg_test` package (black-box) for true public-API tests; same `pkg` package for internal-detail tests.
- **Mocks**: prefer hand-written fakes (in-memory map implementing the store interface). Generated mocks (`mockery`, `gomock`) only for large stable interfaces. Never mock what you don't own — wrap the third-party type in your own interface, mock that.
- **Integration tests with `testcontainers-go`** for real Postgres / Redis / LocalStack — spins a Docker container per test (or per package via `TestMain`), tears it down. Gate with `//go:build integration` so unit tests stay fast.
- HTTP handlers: `httptest.NewRecorder()` + `handler.ServeHTTP(rr, req)`; assert on `rr.Code` / `rr.Body`. Full server: `httptest.NewServer(mux)`.
- Coverage: `go test -coverprofile=cov.out -covermode=atomic ./...`. Don't chase 100% — chase critical paths and edge cases. **`go test -race`** non-negotiable in CI. Fuzz (`func FuzzXxx(f *testing.F)`) for parsers, validators, anything taking untrusted bytes.

```go
// internal/user/service_test.go
func TestService_GetByID(t *testing.T) {
    t.Parallel()
    cases := []struct {
        name    string
        seed    map[uuid.UUID]User
        id      uuid.UUID
        want    User
        wantErr error
    }{
        {"found", map[uuid.UUID]User{id1: {ID: id1, Email: "a@b.c"}}, id1, User{ID: id1, Email: "a@b.c"}, nil},
        {"not found", nil, id1, User{}, ErrNotFound},
    }
    for _, tc := range cases {
        tc := tc
        t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            t.Parallel()
            svc := NewService(&fakeStore{users: tc.seed})
            got, err := svc.GetByID(context.Background(), tc.id)
            if !errors.Is(err, tc.wantErr) { t.Fatalf("err: got %v, want %v", err, tc.wantErr) }
            if got != tc.want { t.Errorf("user: got %+v, want %+v", got, tc.want) }
        })
    }
}
```

---

## Build, Cross-Compile, Deploy

- `go build` is enough — but a `Makefile` is a fine entry point for `lint`/`test`/`tidy`/`build`/`docker`/`deploy`. CI replays Makefile targets.
- **Reproducible builds**: `-trimpath -ldflags "-s -w -X main.version=${VERSION} -X main.commit=${COMMIT}"`. Inject version/commit via `-X`, not runtime magic.
- **CGO_ENABLED=0** for portable static binaries — required for `FROM scratch` and AL2023 Lambda. CGO only when truly needed (native SQLite, etc.) — base image then becomes `debian-slim` / `alpine`.
- Cross-compile: `GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build` from any host. No emulation; faster than building inside Docker on the target arch.
- **Docker**: multi-stage. Stage 1 `golang:1.24-alpine` builds. Stage 2 `gcr.io/distroless/static-debian12:nonroot` (or `scratch`) copies binary + `ca-certificates` (+ `tzdata` if needed). `USER nonroot:nonroot`. Final image < 20 MB.
- Image scanning (Trivy / Grype) in CI. Critical CVEs in the **final** image (not the build stage) are blockers. Re-scan deployed images on a schedule.
- Deploy artifacts: container images for ECS / EKS / EC2; zip for Lambda. Always tag with the Git SHA — never `latest` in production.

---

## Tooling

- **Required**: `gofmt`/`goimports`, `go vet`, `golangci-lint` with a curated set (`errcheck`, `staticcheck`, `unused`, `ineffassign`, `gosec`, `revive`, `errorlint`, `bodyclose`, `containedctx`, `contextcheck`, `noctx`, `sqlclosecheck`, `paralleltest`, `gocyclo`, `gocritic`, `misspell`). Pin the version in CI; `.golangci.yml` in repo root.
- `govulncheck ./...` and `gosec ./...` in CI per PR. `go test -race ./...` always. `go mod tidy` + `go mod verify` per CI run — fail if files would change.
- **`pprof`**: expose `net/http/pprof` on a separate admin listener (never the public port). Profile in production, not on a laptop. **`benchstat`** for benchmark comparison (`-count=10` minimum) — don't trust single runs.
- IDE: `gopls` with `gopls.staticcheck: true`; `delve` for debugging. Optional: `air`/`wgo`/`reflex` for dev hot-reload; `task` as Make alternative; `goreleaser` for multi-arch release artifacts.

---

## Performance and Resource Tuning

- Profile before optimizing. `go test -bench=. -benchmem -cpuprofile=cpu.out -memprofile=mem.out` at package level; `pprof` for live processes. Don't optimize from intuition.
- **`GOMAXPROCS`**: defaults to host CPU count, which is wrong on Kubernetes / ECS where the container has a CPU limit but the host has many cores — leads to GC contention and scheduler thrash. Use `automaxprocs` (`go.uber.org/automaxprocs`) — reads cgroup limits at startup and sets `GOMAXPROCS` correctly.
- **`GOMEMLIMIT`** (1.19+): set to ~80% of the container memory limit (env in task definition). Runtime GCs harder near the limit, dramatically reducing OOMKills under spikes. With it set, manual `GOGC` tuning is rarely needed (default 100 is fine).
- **Allocations dominate latency** more than CPU in most Go services. `pprof -alloc_objects` to find hotspots. Pre-size slices / maps when capacity known. `sync.Pool` for short-lived objects in hot paths. `strings.Builder` over `+=`. Avoid `[]byte`↔`string` conversions in tight loops.
- HTTP: reuse `http.Client` and its `Transport` (don't allocate per request). Tune `Transport.MaxIdleConnsPerHost` upward (default 2 is too low for backend-to-backend traffic). Always set `Client.Timeout`.

---

## Large Project Maintenance

- **Dependency hygiene**: `go list -m -u all` monthly. `govulncheck` in CI per PR. One major bump per PR. Pin versions in `go.mod`; commit `go.sum`. `go mod why -m <module>` to find what pulls a transitive dep in.
- **Dead code**: `staticcheck`'s `U1000` flags unused; remove ruthlessly. `deadcode` (`golang.org/x/tools/cmd/deadcode`) for cross-package. Don't keep "in case we need it later" — Git remembers.
- **Refactoring**: only when the task requires or you've been asked. Scope tightly — one thing per PR. Tests first, then change. Flag tech debt; don't silently fix it.
- **Migration / large changes**: incremental. New behavior behind a flag (env var, feature flag service); old and new coexist; flip the flag; remove old code in a follow-up PR. Document the canonical pattern in this file.
- **Performance budgets**: SLO per endpoint (p50, p95, p99); CI benchmark check on hot paths; alert on regression (`benchstat -delta-test`). Track service-level metrics in production (RED: rate, errors, duration; USE: utilization, saturation, errors).
- **Module boundaries**: when `internal/` grows beyond ~10 domain packages, consider splitting into multiple modules (monorepo with `go.work`). Don't split prematurely — one module is simpler.

---

## When Creating a New Go Service

1. `go mod init github.com/<org>/<service>`. Set `go 1.24`+. Create `cmd/api/main.go`, `internal/`, `Makefile`, `Dockerfile`, `.golangci.yml`, `.env.example`, `.gitignore`.
2. Wire basics: `slog` JSON, `automaxprocs`, `GOMEMLIMIT`, env loading, graceful shutdown, `/healthz` + `/readyz`. Stdlib `net/http` `ServeMux`.
3. Pick infra: Postgres (`pgx` + `sqlc`) or DynamoDB. Migrations via `golang-migrate`. Pool ping in `/readyz`.
4. OTel init (`otelhttp`, `otelpgx`/`otelaws`). OTLP exporter → ADOT collector sidecar.
5. CI: `go vet`, `go test -race -coverprofile=cov.out ./...`, `golangci-lint run`, `govulncheck ./...`, `go build`, container build + push, integration tests with `testcontainers-go` (`//go:build integration`).
6. Deploy: multi-stage Dockerfile → distroless / scratch; ECS Fargate with distinct task + execution roles (least privilege); CloudWatch logs; ALB or API Gateway; auto-scale on CPU + ALB request count. Lambda variant: `bootstrap` binary, AL2023, arm64. GPU variant: ECS-on-EC2 / EKS, amd64, distroless Go service in front of NIM/Triton container.
7. Commit `.env.example`. Never commit `.env` or AWS creds.

---

## When Working on an Existing Project

1. Read first — `cmd/` entry, `internal/<domain>/`, store impl, related handler, `Makefile`, `Dockerfile`, `.golangci.yml`.
2. Match existing conventions even if they differ from these rules — consistency beats theoretical best practice. If they use `gin` or `chi`, use it; don't migrate without approval.
3. Don't refactor unrelated code; don't add types / comments to code you didn't change; don't introduce new libs without approval. Match existing naming, organization, error-wrapping style.
4. Trace data flow handler → service → store; don't skip layers unless that's the existing pattern. Audit `ctx` propagation on every function in the path; long-running goroutines listen on `ctx.Done()`.
5. Audit observability: new endpoints get spans + metrics + structured logs with request ID; new downstream calls go through `otelhttp` / `otelaws` / `otelpgx`.
6. Run `go vet`, `golangci-lint run`, `go test -race ./...`, `go mod tidy` before committing.

---

## Pre-Completion Checklist

- [ ] `gofmt`, `go vet`, `golangci-lint`, `go test -race`, `go mod tidy`, `govulncheck` all pass (or document why)
- [ ] Every exported identifier has a doc comment starting with its name
- [ ] Every blocking / I/O function takes `ctx context.Context` first; no `context.Background()` in handlers / library code
- [ ] Errors wrapped with `%w` + context; `errors.Is` / `errors.As` (not string compare); none swallowed
- [ ] No `panic` outside `main` startup or recovery middleware; `log.Fatal` only in `main`
- [ ] No SQL built with `fmt.Sprintf` from user input; all queries parameterized; bodies size-capped via `MaxBytesReader`; all input validated
- [ ] No secrets in code, env defaults, logs, or commits; `crypto/rand` for tokens; httpOnly Secure cookies for sessions
- [ ] HTTP server has all four timeouts set; graceful shutdown on SIGTERM
- [ ] Goroutines have obvious termination paths; concurrent map writes guarded; `errgroup` used for parallel fail-fast
- [ ] Logs are structured JSON (`slog`); request + trace IDs propagated; no PII / tokens / `Authorization` headers logged
- [ ] OTel spans cover new business ops + downstream calls; HTTP / DB / AWS auto-instrumented
- [ ] DTOs returned to clients (no raw domain / DB types); error responses have stable shape
- [ ] AWS SDK v2 only; clients are singletons; `ctx` passed; paginators used
- [ ] Dockerfile multi-stage / distroless; `CGO_ENABLED=0`; arch chosen explicitly (arm64 default; amd64 if CGO / GPU / AVX-512 / customer); image scanned
- [ ] GPU work goes through gRPC to Triton/NIM; CUDA not called from Go via CGO; DCGM metrics scraped
- [ ] Tests added: table-driven, `t.Parallel()`, `t.Run` subtests; integration tests tag-gated; race-clean
- [ ] No CI/CD changes without approval; no `go get -u ./...` of unrelated deps; new deps justified

---

